---
import Layout from '../../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Repl from '../../../../components/Repl';
import SchemeRepl from '../../../../components/SchemeRepl';
import Neighbors from "../../../../components/Neighbors.astro";
import PrevNext from "../../../../components/PrevNext.astro";
---

<Layout title="Econ Ch.9 — Price Discrimination" favicon="💰">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/economics/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to economics</a>

    <h1>Price Discrimination</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Adam Smith · 1776 · <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Price_discrimination"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Wikipedia: Price discrimination</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none"><strong>Price discrimination</strong> means charging different prices for the same good based on the buyer's willingness to pay. It comes in three degrees: perfect (unique price per buyer), quantity-based (bulk discounts), and segment-based (student tickets, senior discounts). The seller captures more of the surplus that would otherwise go to consumers.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. First Degree -->
    <h3>First degree: perfect price discrimination</h3>
    <p>The seller charges each buyer their exact maximum willingness to pay. All consumer surplus is captured. In practice this is rare, but personalized pricing algorithms approximate it. Auctions are a close real-world mechanism.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; First degree: charge each buyer their max willingness to pay
; Buyers have different reservation prices

(define buyers '(50 40 35 25 20 15))
(define cost 10)

; Uniform pricing at $25
(define uniform-price 25)
(define (uniform-profit buyers price cost)
  (let ((sold (filter (lambda (b) (>= b price)) buyers)))
    (* (length sold) (- price cost))))

(display "Uniform price $25, profit: $")
(display (uniform-profit buyers uniform-price cost))
(newline)

; Perfect discrimination: charge each buyer their reservation price
(define (perfect-profit buyers cost)
  (apply + (map (lambda (b) (if (>= b cost) (- b cost) 0)) buyers)))

(display "Perfect discrimination, profit: $")
(display (perfect-profit buyers cost))
(newline)

; Consumer surplus under each regime
(define (consumer-surplus buyers price)
  (apply + (map (lambda (b) (if (>= b price) (- b price) 0)) buyers)))

(display "Consumer surplus (uniform): $")
(display (consumer-surplus buyers uniform-price))
(newline)

(display "Consumer surplus (perfect): $0")
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# First degree price discrimination
buyers = [50, 40, 35, 25, 20, 15]
cost = 10

# Uniform pricing
price = 25
sold = [b for b in buyers if b >= price]
uniform_profit = len(sold) * (price - cost)
print("Uniform price $" + str(price) + ", profit: $" + str(uniform_profit))

# Perfect discrimination
perfect_profit = sum(b - cost for b in buyers if b >= cost)
print("Perfect discrimination, profit: $" + str(perfect_profit))

# Consumer surplus
cs_uniform = sum(b - price for b in buyers if b >= price)
print("Consumer surplus (uniform): $" + str(cs_uniform))
print("Consumer surplus (perfect): $0")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- 2. Second Degree -->
    <h3>Second degree: quantity discounts</h3>
    <p>The seller offers different price-quantity packages. Buyers self-select into tiers. Think bulk discounts, software licensing tiers, or phone data plans. The seller doesn't need to know each buyer's type; the menu is designed so each type prefers the package meant for them.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Second degree: quantity discounts
; Buyers self-select into tiers

(define (tier-price quantity)
  (cond
    ((>= quantity 100) 8)   ; bulk: $8/unit
    ((>= quantity 10) 10)   ; medium: $10/unit
    (else 15)))             ; single: $15/unit

(define (total-cost quantity)
  (* quantity (tier-price quantity)))

(display "1 unit:   $") (display (total-cost 1)) (newline)
(display "10 units: $") (display (total-cost 10)) (newline)
(display "50 units: $") (display (total-cost 50)) (newline)
(display "100 units: $") (display (total-cost 100)) (newline)

; Per-unit price falls with quantity
(display "Per-unit at 1:   $") (display (tier-price 1)) (newline)
(display "Per-unit at 50:  $") (display (tier-price 50)) (newline)
(display "Per-unit at 100: $") (display (tier-price 100))
`} />


    <!-- 3. Third Degree -->
    <h3>Third degree: market segmentation</h3>
    <p>The seller divides buyers into identifiable groups and charges each group a different price. Student discounts, senior pricing, geographic pricing, matinee tickets. The requirement: the seller must be able to identify group membership and prevent resale between groups.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Same product, three price levels -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 400 200" class="w-full max-w-md" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Product -->
        <rect x="150" y="10" width="100" height="40" rx="6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.6"/>
        <text x="200" y="35" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="13" fill-opacity="0.8">Same Product</text>

        <!-- Lines to segments -->
        <line x1="175" y1="50" x2="60" y2="100" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.3"/>
        <line x1="200" y1="50" x2="200" y2="100" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.3"/>
        <line x1="225" y1="50" x2="340" y2="100" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.3"/>

        <!-- Segment A: Business -->
        <rect x="10" y="100" width="100" height="80" rx="6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="60" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.6">Business</text>
        <text x="60" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="18" fill-opacity="0.9">$800</text>
        <text x="60" y="172" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">low elasticity</text>

        <!-- Segment B: Regular -->
        <rect x="150" y="100" width="100" height="80" rx="6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="200" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.6">Regular</text>
        <text x="200" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="18" fill-opacity="0.9">$350</text>
        <text x="200" y="172" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">medium elasticity</text>

        <!-- Segment C: Student -->
        <rect x="290" y="100" width="100" height="80" rx="6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" opacity="0.4"/>
        <text x="340" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="11" fill-opacity="0.6">Student</text>
        <text x="340" y="155" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="18" fill-opacity="0.9">$150</text>
        <text x="340" y="172" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">high elasticity</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Airline pricing: third degree price discrimination
; Same seat, different prices by segment

(define segments
  '(("Business"  800  20 0.3)   ; (name price quantity elasticity)
    ("Regular"   350  80 1.0)
    ("Student"   150  40 2.5)))

(define cost-per-seat 100)

(define (segment-profit seg)
  (let ((price (cadr seg))
        (qty (caddr seg)))
    (* qty (- price cost-per-seat))))

(define (show-segment seg)
  (display (car seg))
  (display ": ")
  (display (cadr seg))
  (display " x ")
  (display (caddr seg))
  (display " = $")
  (display (segment-profit seg))
  (newline))

(for-each show-segment segments)

(define total (apply + (map segment-profit segments)))
(display "Total profit: $")
(display total)
(newline)

; Compare to uniform price of $350
(define uniform-qty 100)  ; lose some business, gain some students
(define uniform-profit (* uniform-qty (- 350 cost-per-seat)))
(display "Uniform at $350 (100 seats): $")
(display uniform-profit)
`} />


